1
00:00:50,508 --> 00:00:51,248
My name's Journey.

2
00:00:51,468 --> 00:00:52,848
I'm a documentary filmmaker

3
00:00:52,848 --> 00:00:54,888
and sometimes I wish I were dead,

4
00:00:55,908 --> 00:00:57,128
but more on that in a minute.

5
00:00:57,868 --> 00:00:58,888
I'm deeply concerned

6
00:00:58,888 --> 00:01:00,768
by the war on science in our culture
today.

7
00:01:00,768 --> 00:01:02,808
Whether we're talking about the climate
crisis,

8
00:01:03,268 --> 00:01:04,448
global pandemics,

9
00:01:04,548 --> 00:01:07,888
or the mysteries of our own brains,
science is integral

10
00:01:07,888 --> 00:01:09,528
to finding meaningful solutions.

11
00:01:10,548 --> 00:01:12,688
And so is talking to each other.
Sometimes,

12
00:01:12,758 --> 00:01:15,928
growing up American has made me feel like
I'm at a giant

13
00:01:15,988 --> 00:01:18,768
family holiday where both parents hate
each other.

14
00:01:18,988 --> 00:01:21,328
The family dog has died and the house is
on fire

15
00:01:22,228 --> 00:01:24,968
and it's got roaches and the plumbing is
bad.

16
00:01:25,648 --> 00:01:27,208
I wish we knew how to talk to each other.

17
00:01:28,298 --> 00:01:31,048
Sadly, like millions of other people, I
also struggle

18
00:01:31,048 --> 00:01:32,968
with depression. To be frank,

19
00:01:33,088 --> 00:01:34,728
I can get really depressed...

20
00:01:35,188 --> 00:01:37,168
and while it's easy to point to the
environment,

21
00:01:37,228 --> 00:01:39,048
the way we treat each other, the fact

22
00:01:39,048 --> 00:01:41,648
that everyone we love will die, YouTube
ads,

23
00:01:41,708 --> 00:01:43,088
and meetings that could have been emails,

24
00:01:43,708 --> 00:01:47,128
the truth is, I often feel blue on good
days too.

25
00:01:47,708 --> 00:01:52,008
You can lose 30 pounds, quit drinking,
quit smoking,

26
00:01:52,558 --> 00:01:55,528
make an effort to go outside more, eat
healthier,

27
00:01:55,678 --> 00:01:57,168
basically do everything right

28
00:01:58,068 --> 00:02:00,608
and still be super f*****g depressed.

29
00:02:00,958 --> 00:02:02,008
With all of this in mind,

30
00:02:02,168 --> 00:02:03,728
I have seriously considered taking

31
00:02:03,728 --> 00:02:05,968
antidepressants, although I am hesitant.

32
00:02:06,448 --> 00:02:08,288
I know people who've been really helped
by meds

33
00:02:08,288 --> 00:02:10,048
and others who have killed themselves

34
00:02:10,098 --> 00:02:12,168
after getting on a new antidepressant.

35
00:02:12,678 --> 00:02:16,208
Studies show, in some cases, taking
antidepressants can

36
00:02:16,488 --> 00:02:18,288
actually increase the risk of suicide.

37
00:02:18,758 --> 00:02:21,688
Obviously, I wanted to know more before
making a decision.

38
00:02:22,188 --> 00:02:24,608
So, I started reading about how these
drugs are tested

39
00:02:24,708 --> 00:02:26,008
for safety, which led me

40
00:02:26,008 --> 00:02:28,328
to a paper on NIH'S website explaining

41
00:02:28,328 --> 00:02:30,688
that a common antidepressant testing
method

42
00:02:31,268 --> 00:02:33,888
is something called "the forced swim
test."

43
00:02:34,568 --> 00:02:36,488
Apparently, this test involves putting a
mouse

44
00:02:36,548 --> 00:02:38,288
or a rat into a cylinder of water

45
00:02:38,318 --> 00:02:41,368
that they can't escape from and timing
how long it takes

46
00:02:41,388 --> 00:02:43,488
before they stop swimming.

47
00:02:43,958 --> 00:02:46,248
This is supposed to simulate depression
in humans?

48
00:02:46,598 --> 00:02:49,568
Another rodent is then injected with the
antidepressant

49
00:02:49,628 --> 00:02:52,128
and forced to swim to see if they'll swim
for longer.

50
00:02:52,558 --> 00:02:55,128
Does this mean antidepressants will make
me a better swimmer

51
00:02:55,788 --> 00:02:56,888
or hate my life less?

52
00:02:57,848 --> 00:03:00,088
I also realize these aren't even safety
tests.

53
00:03:00,258 --> 00:03:02,488
These tests are to see if the drugs are
effective.

54
00:03:02,828 --> 00:03:06,128
The idea that the swimming ability of a
rat has anything

55
00:03:06,128 --> 00:03:09,088
to do with my depression seemed pretty
ridiculous.

56
00:03:09,648 --> 00:03:12,168
I couldn't imagine researchers testing
antidepressants

57
00:03:12,168 --> 00:03:13,248
with a human swim test.

58
00:03:13,998 --> 00:03:15,928
Over 280 million people

59
00:03:16,028 --> 00:03:18,128
around the world suffer from depression.

60
00:03:19,028 --> 00:03:21,648
For myself, I know that this can be a
devastating,

61
00:03:22,228 --> 00:03:24,608
joy-robbing, even life-threatening
illness.

62
00:03:25,308 --> 00:03:28,208
The total impact of mental illness on a
person's life is

63
00:03:28,208 --> 00:03:30,728
difficult to measure, but the outcomes
are clear enough.

64
00:03:30,958 --> 00:03:33,288
Suicide is a leading cause of death among
young people,

65
00:03:33,628 --> 00:03:36,368
and those with severe mental health
problems can die decades

66
00:03:36,498 --> 00:03:38,888
early from preventable physical
conditions.

67
00:03:39,398 --> 00:03:40,448
It's hard to stay healthy

68
00:03:40,668 --> 00:03:44,368
and hopeful when you feel neither. People
are suffering

69
00:03:44,468 --> 00:03:45,608
and dying, and yet

70
00:03:45,608 --> 00:03:48,448
what seemed like an absurd testing method
was being used.

71
00:03:48,668 --> 00:03:51,208
But I'm not a scientist, so I wanted to
speak

72
00:03:51,208 --> 00:03:52,608
with actual researchers

73
00:03:53,028 --> 00:03:54,608
to see if I could understand this better.

74
00:03:54,968 --> 00:03:56,688
I reached out to the lead authors on a
number

75
00:03:56,688 --> 00:03:57,848
of antidepressant papers

76
00:03:57,988 --> 00:03:59,528
to get their insights on this method.

77
00:04:00,008 --> 00:04:02,168
I knew I could go down a Google rabbit
hole with all

78
00:04:02,168 --> 00:04:04,048
of my questions, but that's also

79
00:04:04,048 --> 00:04:05,488
what my flat-earther uncle does.

80
00:04:06,008 --> 00:04:07,768
I wanted to talk to actual scientists

81
00:04:07,768 --> 00:04:09,688
and get a better understanding of what's
going on.

82
00:04:10,488 --> 00:04:11,968
I was able to sit down with Dr.

83
00:04:12,118 --> 00:04:14,208
Neal Barnard, a leading researcher

84
00:04:14,228 --> 00:04:15,968
and president of the Physicians Committee

85
00:04:16,028 --> 00:04:17,688
for Responsible Medicine.

86
00:04:17,688 --> 00:04:20,368
The forced swim test emerged in the 1970s

87
00:04:20,368 --> 00:04:23,008
because researchers were trying to find
some way to

88
00:04:23,928 --> 00:04:25,368
quantify depression.

89
00:04:25,508 --> 00:04:28,368
So, rather than have people just describe
their low moods,

90
00:04:28,668 --> 00:04:29,968
you could put a number to it.

91
00:04:30,278 --> 00:04:33,128
Rats or mice are put into a tank of water.

92
00:04:33,238 --> 00:04:34,888
They can't escape, they can't get out.

93
00:04:34,888 --> 00:04:37,488
They're gonna struggle and eventually
they're gonna just

94
00:04:37,598 --> 00:04:39,288
give up and stop struggling.

95
00:04:39,308 --> 00:04:41,128
And this is all quantified with a
stopwatch,

96
00:04:41,668 --> 00:04:42,808
but it's been discredited.

97
00:04:42,908 --> 00:04:46,088
It really does not apply to the depression

98
00:04:46,088 --> 00:04:47,888
that a person would feel, but to this day,

99
00:04:48,068 --> 00:04:49,408
it is unfortunately used

100
00:04:49,548 --> 00:04:53,408
to compare antidepressants, one versus
another

101
00:04:53,428 --> 00:04:55,168
or an antidepressant versus a placebo.

102
00:04:55,428 --> 00:04:56,968
The forced swim test isn't done

103
00:04:56,968 --> 00:04:58,888
because it's really like human depression.

104
00:04:58,958 --> 00:05:00,728
It's done because you can get a number

105
00:05:00,868 --> 00:05:03,448
and experimenters love numbers.

106
00:05:05,088 --> 00:05:07,448
I love science, but what I just heard,

107
00:05:08,108 --> 00:05:09,728
it didn't sound very scientific.

108
00:05:10,588 --> 00:05:12,688
It sounded alarmingly unscientific.

109
00:05:13,588 --> 00:05:16,208
It sounded like my cousin Barney threw a
rat in the pool,

110
00:05:16,628 --> 00:05:18,448
set his stopwatch and called it science.

111
00:05:20,088 --> 00:05:22,488
I also recognize that using animals in
research

112
00:05:22,488 --> 00:05:24,408
and testing is super controversial.

113
00:05:25,608 --> 00:05:29,368
A Pew Research Center survey from 2018
found that 47%

114
00:05:29,368 --> 00:05:33,128
of Americans favor the practice while 52%
oppose it.

115
00:05:33,828 --> 00:05:36,088
Not unlike the divide between fans of
country music

116
00:05:36,188 --> 00:05:39,448
and everyone else. I myself like animals

117
00:05:39,588 --> 00:05:40,648
and don't want to harm them,

118
00:05:41,148 --> 00:05:42,448
but I also like the idea

119
00:05:42,448 --> 00:05:44,448
of people getting life-saving medications.

120
00:05:45,208 --> 00:05:47,888
I really wanted greater clarity on this
antidepressant

121
00:05:48,128 --> 00:05:49,448
question before I pulled the trigger.

122
00:05:49,948 --> 00:05:51,968
But the study authors still weren't
responding.

123
00:05:52,268 --> 00:05:53,568
The whole thing left me wondering,

124
00:05:53,988 --> 00:05:55,368
how do we know drugs are safe?

125
00:05:55,728 --> 00:05:56,808
I know I'm not the first one

126
00:05:56,808 --> 00:06:00,168
to ask this question: from the people who
refuse vaccination

127
00:06:00,228 --> 00:06:02,448
to those who have gotten all of their
booster shots,

128
00:06:03,068 --> 00:06:06,048
no one seems to have complete faith in
Big Pharma's loving,

129
00:06:06,088 --> 00:06:07,288
humanitarian mission.

130
00:06:07,948 --> 00:06:09,528
So, how are drugs even developed?

131
00:06:09,928 --> 00:06:12,288
I went to speak with premier researcher,
biochemist

132
00:06:12,288 --> 00:06:13,888
and science policy expert, Dr.

133
00:06:14,248 --> 00:06:15,808
Charu Chandrasekera.

134
00:06:15,888 --> 00:06:18,008
In order to bring a drug to market, we
have to go

135
00:06:18,008 --> 00:06:21,088
through a long process that takes decades
of time

136
00:06:21,468 --> 00:06:22,848
and costs billions of dollars.

137
00:06:23,218 --> 00:06:26,288
First, you have to study the molecular
basis of disease,

138
00:06:26,468 --> 00:06:28,728
and this is what's known as biomedical
research.

139
00:06:28,748 --> 00:06:31,848
And this could take decades just to
understand the simple

140
00:06:32,728 --> 00:06:33,688
molecule in the cell, how

141
00:06:33,688 --> 00:06:35,168
that interacts with everything else.

142
00:06:35,278 --> 00:06:37,368
Then you go through the drug development
process,

143
00:06:37,928 --> 00:06:39,568
figuring out what kind of compounds

144
00:06:39,568 --> 00:06:41,768
and selecting it down from like 10,000

145
00:06:42,088 --> 00:06:43,288
compounds to maybe 10.

146
00:06:43,558 --> 00:06:45,448
Then you go through animal testing,
what's known

147
00:06:45,448 --> 00:06:46,448
as preclinical testing,

148
00:06:46,828 --> 00:06:49,168
and then you proceed to human clinical
trials.

149
00:06:49,508 --> 00:06:51,848
And after that, if they pass the clinical
trials,

150
00:06:51,988 --> 00:06:54,248
you go into regulatory approval process

151
00:06:54,298 --> 00:06:57,208
where you would submit your application
for a new drug

152
00:06:57,388 --> 00:06:58,888
to agencies like the Food

153
00:06:58,888 --> 00:07:00,408
and Drug Administration and Health Canada.

154
00:07:01,028 --> 00:07:02,648
The federal government does require

155
00:07:02,918 --> 00:07:04,688
that animal safety tests be done

156
00:07:04,688 --> 00:07:06,448
and it's typically in a rodent species

157
00:07:06,588 --> 00:07:11,528
and a non-rodent species like a dog or a
monkey.

158
00:07:11,768 --> 00:07:13,288
A drug is not allowed to be on the market

159
00:07:13,308 --> 00:07:14,368
unless it goes through those.

160
00:07:15,008 --> 00:07:17,328
I assume drugs are required to be tested
on animals

161
00:07:17,428 --> 00:07:18,528
to ensure that they're safe.

162
00:07:18,868 --> 00:07:22,608
But then I found out that over 14,000 FDA
approved drugs

163
00:07:22,608 --> 00:07:25,248
have been recalled in the last 10 years,
which is a level

164
00:07:25,248 --> 00:07:28,128
of failure not otherwise seen outside of
my Tinder profile.

165
00:07:29,188 --> 00:07:30,688
And a 2017 study

166
00:07:30,688 --> 00:07:33,128
of drugs approved within a 10 year period
found

167
00:07:33,128 --> 00:07:35,328
that the FDA announced alerts, warnings,

168
00:07:35,348 --> 00:07:37,768
or recalls on about one third of them.

169
00:07:38,248 --> 00:07:40,648
I reached out to the FDA for an interview
to find out

170
00:07:40,648 --> 00:07:43,288
what the hell any of this means, but they
declined.

171
00:07:43,838 --> 00:07:46,008
They did answer a few of my questions via
email.

172
00:07:46,468 --> 00:07:48,528
One major part that stood out to me was

173
00:07:48,528 --> 00:07:51,288
that the FDA doesn't usually test drug
safety themselves.

174
00:07:51,718 --> 00:07:53,728
Instead, they rely on the drug companies

175
00:07:53,728 --> 00:07:55,568
to submit accurate data for review.

176
00:07:55,868 --> 00:07:58,768
And that makes sense to me because I,
too, used to take drugs

177
00:07:58,828 --> 00:08:00,608
my associates had already tested for me.

178
00:08:01,168 --> 00:08:02,448
I was able to sit down with Dr.

179
00:08:02,578 --> 00:08:04,688
Aysha Akhtar, public health specialist

180
00:08:04,688 --> 00:08:08,048
and neuroscientist with a decade of
experience at the FDA.

181
00:08:08,728 --> 00:08:12,488
A recent major analysis just was
published that showed

182
00:08:12,718 --> 00:08:17,408
that adverse events from drugs is the
fourth leading cause

183
00:08:17,468 --> 00:08:19,048
of death in the United States.

184
00:08:19,828 --> 00:08:21,328
I'm sorry, I did not know that. It's the
fourth,

185
00:08:21,328 --> 00:08:23,088
the fourth leading cause of death in the,

186
00:08:23,088 --> 00:08:24,848
you mean, like, up there with, like,
heart disease?

187
00:08:25,108 --> 00:08:27,208
The fourth leading cause of death.

188
00:08:28,328 --> 00:08:29,628
Now that's, that's ridiculous.

189
00:08:30,008 --> 00:08:31,108
We can prevent that

190
00:08:31,568 --> 00:08:34,628
by using more human-relevant testing
methods, methods

191
00:08:34,698 --> 00:08:36,748
that will more reliably tell us whether

192
00:08:36,748 --> 00:08:38,708
or not a drug is going to be safe in
humans.

193
00:08:40,068 --> 00:08:41,468
I struggled to believe what I was hearing,

194
00:08:42,128 --> 00:08:44,468
but sure enough, the study was right
there on

195
00:08:44,468 --> 00:08:45,628
the FDA's own website.

196
00:08:46,528 --> 00:08:47,668
Dr. Thomas Hartung

197
00:08:47,668 --> 00:08:50,748
of Johns Hopkins University only added to
my shock

198
00:08:51,178 --> 00:08:53,588
Drug interactions and drug side effects
are

199
00:08:53,788 --> 00:08:55,028
actually a quite severe problem.

200
00:08:55,278 --> 00:08:59,168
More than 100,000 patients which goes in
the hospital

201
00:08:59,878 --> 00:09:02,128
dies from the consequences of the drug
treatments.

202
00:09:02,748 --> 00:09:04,328
So this is really quite a number

203
00:09:04,668 --> 00:09:05,768
and I think that a lot

204
00:09:05,768 --> 00:09:08,168
of this is still not even noticed and
discovered

205
00:09:08,448 --> 00:09:10,688
because very often we attribute these
things to the disease

206
00:09:11,268 --> 00:09:13,528
and we don't have control over the

207
00:09:13,908 --> 00:09:15,008
the side effects of drugs.

208
00:09:15,738 --> 00:09:17,128
Could the regulations in place

209
00:09:17,188 --> 00:09:19,888
to ensure drug safety be an ineffective
formality

210
00:09:20,478 --> 00:09:22,088
like an apology from the Vatican?

211
00:09:23,328 --> 00:09:25,448
I spoke with drug development policy
experts

212
00:09:25,548 --> 00:09:27,448
to get a better understanding.

213
00:09:27,848 --> 00:09:31,168
When companies put drugs into a clinical trial

214
00:09:31,468 --> 00:09:35,328
or out onto the market, that is still an
experiment

215
00:09:35,638 --> 00:09:40,088
because we don't have human relevant
preclinical

216
00:09:40,578 --> 00:09:42,168
tests that are telling us

217
00:09:42,318 --> 00:09:44,848
what the potential adverse reactions
might be.

218
00:09:45,198 --> 00:09:46,928
It's very common for a new drug

219
00:09:46,978 --> 00:09:51,248
after a few years on the market, the
packaging is revised.

220
00:09:51,428 --> 00:09:55,008
So there needs to be a black box warning
that says, oops,

221
00:09:55,788 --> 00:09:57,488
we realize that this causes some

222
00:09:57,818 --> 00:09:59,168
major heart problem in people.

223
00:09:59,548 --> 00:10:01,808
We did not anticipate this from all of
the studies

224
00:10:01,808 --> 00:10:04,168
that we did using hundreds of thousands

225
00:10:04,168 --> 00:10:05,248
of animals over a decade.

226
00:10:05,548 --> 00:10:08,608
The current system that relies on animal
testing information

227
00:10:08,958 --> 00:10:10,448
doesn't give us the full truth.

228
00:10:10,848 --> 00:10:13,128
I don't think many people have a sense

229
00:10:13,128 --> 00:10:15,728
of pure confidence in the decision making

230
00:10:15,728 --> 00:10:18,208
that drug companies and government
agencies do.

231
00:10:18,528 --> 00:10:21,208
A great example of that is Vioxx, a drug

232
00:10:21,208 --> 00:10:24,528
that started causing people to have heart
attacks.

233
00:10:24,868 --> 00:10:26,848
And only after that happened

234
00:10:26,868 --> 00:10:29,968
and the drug was pulled, did we find out
that the maker

235
00:10:29,988 --> 00:10:34,048
of the drug had tweaked its preclinical
animal data in order

236
00:10:34,048 --> 00:10:36,408
just to grease the tracks and get its
drug to market.

237
00:10:36,938 --> 00:10:38,168
Vioxx was safe

238
00:10:38,468 --> 00:10:41,248
and effective in multiple animal models,

239
00:10:41,248 --> 00:10:44,688
including a primate model, but it killed
many thousands

240
00:10:44,748 --> 00:10:47,568
and thousands plus plus plus people
around the globe.

241
00:10:47,628 --> 00:10:52,128
95% of all new drugs that pass

242
00:10:52,128 --> 00:10:53,288
through animal tests,

243
00:10:54,358 --> 00:10:56,568
once they reach human clinical trials,
they fail.

244
00:11:00,638 --> 00:11:03,448
Okay, not exactly, but this is very close
to how I feel.

245
00:11:03,828 --> 00:11:06,808
If this is true, that's absolutely
ludicrous.

246
00:11:07,588 --> 00:11:11,888
95%? 95%?! Is all

247
00:11:11,888 --> 00:11:13,888
of medicine developed with a forced swim
test?

248
00:11:14,298 --> 00:11:16,448
Maybe the best treatment for my
depression is

249
00:11:16,448 --> 00:11:17,848
to just stop asking questions.

250
00:11:18,428 --> 00:11:21,688
Indeed, biophysicist Dr. Francis Cheng
points out

251
00:11:21,688 --> 00:11:22,768
that it actually gets worse.

252
00:11:22,988 --> 00:11:25,728
95%, that's the average. In cancer.

253
00:11:26,028 --> 00:11:30,848
that's 96.6 of the time. In Alzheimer's,
99.6 of the time.

254
00:11:31,488 --> 00:11:36,048
HIV vaccine, stroke, sepsis... a hundred
percent of the time.

255
00:11:36,388 --> 00:11:38,408
And that's all failure - like, a hundred
percent

256
00:11:38,588 --> 00:11:41,088
of the time failure, like, you can't get
worse than that.

257
00:11:41,628 --> 00:11:42,888
So think about it like this:

