they can't sleep, and if you give them
estrogens,

753
00:33:18,448 --> 00:33:19,608
some of those symptoms go away.

754
00:33:19,788 --> 00:33:22,008
The question was, could it also help
their heart?

755
00:33:22,108 --> 00:33:23,688
And in animal studies, you could show

756
00:33:23,878 --> 00:33:26,688
that hormone replacement therapy really
did

757
00:33:26,718 --> 00:33:27,808
seem to be a benefit.

758
00:33:28,318 --> 00:33:30,608
However, two huge trials put this

759
00:33:30,608 --> 00:33:33,568
to the test in human beings. The studies
had to be stopped

760
00:33:33,568 --> 00:33:35,368
because the women were having heart
attacks

761
00:33:35,708 --> 00:33:36,768
as a result of the treatment.

762
00:33:36,768 --> 00:33:38,248
And so researchers went back and they
said, wait,

763
00:33:38,248 --> 00:33:39,808
the animal studies said this ought to be
safe.

764
00:33:40,268 --> 00:33:41,888
It turned out that the animal studies

765
00:33:42,118 --> 00:33:43,928
that disagreed were just being left out.

766
00:33:43,958 --> 00:33:45,368
They were just not being published.

767
00:33:45,468 --> 00:33:48,328
It was a massive case of publication
bias. Why?

768
00:33:48,518 --> 00:33:50,768
Because nobody requires you to publish

769
00:33:51,368 --> 00:33:52,888
a study if you don't like the results

770
00:33:53,828 --> 00:33:57,008
if the subjects were animals. If the
subjects were animals,

771
00:33:57,008 --> 00:33:58,048
you can just throw it away.

772
00:33:58,268 --> 00:34:00,008
Cherry picking results,

773
00:34:00,608 --> 00:34:03,248
dropping those experiments which "did not
work,"

774
00:34:03,248 --> 00:34:05,728
very often leads us to research which
cannot

775
00:34:05,788 --> 00:34:07,008
be reproduced by others.

776
00:34:07,008 --> 00:34:08,648
Meaning that the results are not real.

777
00:34:09,108 --> 00:34:10,408
The results are not true

778
00:34:10,948 --> 00:34:13,808
and this is a huge issue in preclinical
testing

779
00:34:13,838 --> 00:34:15,968
because it's so rampant.

780
00:34:16,198 --> 00:34:20,608
What it means is that all of the money
that

781
00:34:21,348 --> 00:34:23,248
we as taxpayers have spent

782
00:34:23,758 --> 00:34:27,208
producing those experimental results
might be wasted.

783
00:34:27,778 --> 00:34:30,688
Major pharmaceutical companies like Amgen
have found

784
00:34:30,688 --> 00:34:32,128
that up to 89%

785
00:34:32,128 --> 00:34:34,888
of the academic studies they base their
new drug development

786
00:34:34,908 --> 00:34:38,728
on cannot be reproduced... much like the
golden age of hip hop.

787
00:34:39,028 --> 00:34:40,528
And that's only reproducibility

788
00:34:40,548 --> 00:34:43,928
for studies involving the same species,
like a rat to a rat

789
00:34:43,928 --> 00:34:44,928
or a dog to a dog,

790
00:34:45,348 --> 00:34:47,408
and doesn't even look at the fundamental
problem

791
00:34:47,508 --> 00:34:50,888
of translating those results to actual
human beings.

792
00:34:51,668 --> 00:34:54,968
One area where this is particularly
worrisome is toxicology.

793
00:34:55,218 --> 00:34:57,208
Toxicology testing is very important.

794
00:34:57,398 --> 00:35:00,248
It's basically helping us understand the
safety

795
00:35:00,588 --> 00:35:02,368
or potential toxicities of chemicals

796
00:35:02,508 --> 00:35:04,848
and then making decisions about how

797
00:35:04,868 --> 00:35:07,048
to protect humans and the environment.

798
00:35:07,318 --> 00:35:09,048
Most of the tests that are used

799
00:35:09,148 --> 00:35:13,048
for regulatory toxicology testing today
were developed 50

800
00:35:13,108 --> 00:35:14,448
to 80 plus years ago.

801
00:35:14,548 --> 00:35:18,568
So these are tests that have been
basically grandfathered in

802
00:35:18,748 --> 00:35:21,448
as acceptable, but they were never
formally validated

803
00:35:21,588 --> 00:35:24,448
for their reliability or relevance to
humans.

804
00:35:24,918 --> 00:35:26,248
Well, those tests tell you

805
00:35:26,398 --> 00:35:28,808
what would happen if you put a chemical
in a rabbit's eye

806
00:35:29,348 --> 00:35:32,768
or what would happen if you force fed a
chemical to a rat.

807
00:35:33,118 --> 00:35:34,688
They don't necessarily tell you

808
00:35:34,688 --> 00:35:37,328
what would happen if humans are exposed
to that chemical.

809
00:35:37,568 --> 00:35:38,568
To give you one example

810
00:35:38,568 --> 00:35:40,328
here, a few years ago,

811
00:35:40,518 --> 00:35:44,288
Coca-Cola was forced to change a dye in
Coke

812
00:35:44,288 --> 00:35:47,768
because of an animal test where cancer
was developed

813
00:35:47,768 --> 00:35:50,368
in rats. The equivalent dose we would need

814
00:35:50,368 --> 00:35:53,368
to drink is 8,000 cans of Coke per day.

815
00:35:53,908 --> 00:35:56,088
That's the dose at which cancer developed.

816
00:35:56,188 --> 00:35:58,168
So it's a completely irrelevant finding,

817
00:35:58,388 --> 00:36:01,848
and this shows how crazy the economical
consequences are

818
00:36:02,068 --> 00:36:03,168
of an animal test

819
00:36:03,168 --> 00:36:05,048
which is simply not properly doing the
job.

820
00:36:05,468 --> 00:36:07,848
Dr. Hartung calls it a "completely
irrelevant finding,"

821
00:36:08,148 --> 00:36:09,928
but apparently he doesn't remember what
it's like

822
00:36:09,928 --> 00:36:12,288
to be a sugar addicted 10-year-old with a
dream.

823
00:36:13,178 --> 00:36:16,208
Let's be honest, we use animals in
research every day.

824
00:36:16,828 --> 00:36:20,248
The area I work mostly in, which is
toxicology policy,

825
00:36:20,778 --> 00:36:23,848
right now still involves a lot of animal
testing.

826
00:36:24,668 --> 00:36:26,288
But what we're seeing is

827
00:36:26,318 --> 00:36:27,888
that we're bumping up against some

828
00:36:27,888 --> 00:36:28,928
limits in the use of animals.

829
00:36:29,108 --> 00:36:32,288
We have to evolve the tests that don't
use animals, tests

830
00:36:32,838 --> 00:36:34,928
that really focus on human biology

831
00:36:35,428 --> 00:36:36,768
and give us information about

832
00:36:36,788 --> 00:36:39,008
how things react in human systems.

833
00:36:39,388 --> 00:36:42,248
If I want to know whether the substance
is producing

834
00:36:42,248 --> 00:36:44,448
cancer, the standard approach today is

835
00:36:44,468 --> 00:36:46,128
to run a cancer bioassay.

836
00:36:46,318 --> 00:36:48,208
This will give you results in about five
years.

837
00:36:48,308 --> 00:36:52,448
You pay around $1 million for testing a
single substance.

838
00:36:52,628 --> 00:36:54,408
So most stuff comes to the market

839
00:36:54,468 --> 00:36:56,688
and has never been tested, whether it's
producing cancer

840
00:36:56,748 --> 00:36:59,208
or not, because they don't want to wait
for five years

841
00:36:59,508 --> 00:37:02,288
to get this. Time to market is most
critical.

842
00:37:02,898 --> 00:37:05,008
Maybe it's naive of me to be surprised

843
00:37:05,008 --> 00:37:07,048
that money would come before public
safety,

844
00:37:07,508 --> 00:37:11,568
but as my mom would say, I'm not mad, I'm
just disappointed.

845
00:37:11,828 --> 00:37:13,928
The FDA and EPA are supposed

846
00:37:13,928 --> 00:37:15,568
to be protecting us from toxins,

847
00:37:16,068 --> 00:37:18,728
but they've been fighting a losing battle
against a growing

848
00:37:18,798 --> 00:37:21,248
list of unknown and untested substances

849
00:37:21,378 --> 00:37:22,568
since at least the eighties.

850
00:37:23,238 --> 00:37:25,248
From toxicology to basic research,

851
00:37:25,708 --> 00:37:28,288
it turns out the government is a big part
of the problem.

852
00:37:28,708 --> 00:37:30,088
The National Institutes of Health

853
00:37:30,688 --> 00:37:33,528
actually is the largest governmental
funder of research.

854
00:37:33,818 --> 00:37:37,328
About 50% of their funding goes towards
experiments

855
00:37:37,328 --> 00:37:39,048
that include animal experimentation.

856
00:37:39,338 --> 00:37:43,288
Right now, that's $20 billion a year going

857
00:37:43,288 --> 00:37:45,288
to fund animal experiments.

858
00:37:45,758 --> 00:37:49,808
Legislators on Capitol Hill often simply
blindly give NIH

859
00:37:50,128 --> 00:37:52,768
whatever it asks for when it comes to
funding increases

860
00:37:53,068 --> 00:37:55,608
and don't expect any real accountability.

861
00:37:56,168 --> 00:37:58,688
A lot of this money goes to universities

862
00:37:59,298 --> 00:38:01,568
where animal experimenters engage in

863
00:38:01,568 --> 00:38:03,288
what they call "basic research."

864
00:38:03,868 --> 00:38:05,888
So at the University of Wisconsin,
Madison,

865
00:38:06,098 --> 00:38:08,448
there was an experimenter who was taking
cats

866
00:38:09,028 --> 00:38:11,648
and he would intentionally deafen the
cats.

867
00:38:12,158 --> 00:38:15,288
Then he would put metal coils near their
eyes,

868
00:38:15,948 --> 00:38:18,728
cut into their heads, saw off a portion
of the skull,

869
00:38:19,068 --> 00:38:20,248
implant electrodes...

870
00:38:20,428 --> 00:38:22,328
He was extremely explicit.

871
00:38:22,668 --> 00:38:25,848
He said, I'm not looking for a cure for
deafness.

872
00:38:26,428 --> 00:38:28,448
I'm not even looking for a way

873
00:38:28,448 --> 00:38:29,888
to develop better hearing aids.

874
00:38:30,568 --> 00:38:31,888
I just wanna understand what parts

875
00:38:31,888 --> 00:38:34,048
of the brain control sound localization.

876
00:38:34,828 --> 00:38:37,008
And he got tens of millions

877
00:38:37,008 --> 00:38:39,208
of dollars from the National Institutes
of Health.

878
00:38:39,528 --> 00:38:43,488
I think taxpayers would be outraged to
learn that

879
00:38:44,038 --> 00:38:48,088
huge portions of these grants from NIH
given to universities

880
00:38:48,088 --> 00:38:49,648
and colleges aren't going towards
research.

881
00:38:50,078 --> 00:38:52,648
They are going towards the construction
of new buildings.

882
00:38:52,708 --> 00:38:56,048
It could be a new dining hall, it could
be new sidewalk.

883
00:38:56,518 --> 00:38:58,848
They're not necessarily buildings related
to research

884
00:38:58,948 --> 00:39:01,128
or healthcare or improving public health.

885
00:39:01,438 --> 00:39:03,528
They could be anything because every
university gets

886
00:39:03,548 --> 00:39:06,648
to take part of that grant and use it as
it sees fit.

887
00:39:06,648 --> 00:39:09,168
Universities need to keep funds coming in

888
00:39:09,168 --> 00:39:10,448
to keep their departments alive.

889
00:39:10,588 --> 00:39:13,488
And so this is absolutely one of the
drivers

890
00:39:13,708 --> 00:39:15,928
of animal use in experiments

891
00:39:15,928 --> 00:39:18,808
where there is no legal requirement to
conduct these tests.

892
00:39:19,068 --> 00:39:22,048
Animal testing that happens at a
university laboratory,

893
00:39:22,268 --> 00:39:25,048
unless they're developing a drug being
presented to the Food

894
00:39:25,048 --> 00:39:26,768
and Drug Administration or another
regulator,

895
00:39:27,078 --> 00:39:28,808
that testing can end tomorrow.

896
00:39:29,278 --> 00:39:32,888
It's being carried out because a
laboratory wants to do it.

897
00:39:32,978 --> 00:39:34,568
There are so many studies -

898
00:39:34,618 --> 00:39:37,088
there are legacy studies, studies that
were funded

899
00:39:37,188 --> 00:39:38,848
for the last 28 years.

900
00:39:39,798 --> 00:39:42,968
They haven't yielded anything useful for
humans,

901
00:39:43,588 --> 00:39:45,248
and yet they continue to be funded.

902
00:39:45,908 --> 00:39:47,648
At Wayne State University in Detroit,

903
00:39:48,258 --> 00:39:49,808
there are these heart failure

904
00:39:49,908 --> 00:39:51,528
and hypertension dog experiments

905
00:39:51,718 --> 00:39:54,048
that have been going on since 1991.

906
00:39:54,158 --> 00:39:57,208
They've received more than $15 million in
NIH money.

907
00:39:57,588 --> 00:39:59,968
We reviewed all of the papers published
from these studies.

908
00:40:00,268 --> 00:40:02,528
We tried to track down any new treatments

909
00:40:02,628 --> 00:40:04,328
or new devices that have come from these

910
00:40:04,548 --> 00:40:05,768
and we can't find anything.

911
00:40:06,268 --> 00:40:09,128
We wrote to NIH a few years ago to say,

912
00:40:09,268 --> 00:40:10,528
why are you still funding this?

913
00:40:10,828 --> 00:40:13,008
And when they finally wrote us back, they
said,

914
00:40:14,068 --> 00:40:16,568
we looked at the publications from this
research

915
00:40:17,268 --> 00:40:20,368
and we believe those publications are
contributing

916
00:40:20,368 --> 00:40:22,128
to an impressive body of science.

917
00:40:22,668 --> 00:40:24,288
So over the course of three decades,

918
00:40:24,588 --> 00:40:28,448
the only reason NIH continues to fund
these experiments is

919
00:40:28,448 --> 00:40:30,728
because of the published papers, not

920
00:40:30,728 --> 00:40:33,328
because of any tangible outcomes for
patients

921
00:40:33,328 --> 00:40:34,848
who are suffering from heart disease,

922
00:40:34,848 --> 00:40:36,448
hypertension, or heart failure.

923
00:40:37,018 --> 00:40:40,288
There are people at universities who
purport

924
00:40:40,288 --> 00:40:42,208
to study Parkinson's disease.

925
00:40:42,358 --> 00:40:46,528
They might inject a toxin into the brain
so

926
00:40:46,528 --> 00:40:49,088
that the monkeys develop a tremor.

927
00:40:49,348 --> 00:40:52,608
So you're getting the symptom of
Parkinson's,

928
00:40:52,628 --> 00:40:54,208
but that's not Parkinson's.

929
00:40:54,598 --> 00:40:57,768
That is not what's happening in
Parkinson's patients.

930
00:40:58,098 --> 00:40:59,168
These are diseases

931
00:40:59,168 --> 00:41:02,408
that are developing sometimes over
decades,

932
00:41:03,028 --> 00:41:05,528
but that's not what the animal
experimenters are studying.

933
00:41:05,828 --> 00:41:08,328
If they were doing studies to help people

934
00:41:08,348 --> 00:41:10,368
who actually have serious illnesses,

935
00:41:10,368 --> 00:41:12,408
whether we're talking about cancer or
Alzheimer's disease

936
00:41:12,408 --> 00:41:16,368
or others, they would be studying those
human diseases using

937
00:41:16,388 --> 00:41:17,288
the state-of-the-art

938
00:41:17,448 --> 00:41:18,808
research methods that we have available
now.

939
00:41:19,218 --> 00:41:21,808
While today I am mature enough to
recognize

940
00:41:21,888 --> 00:41:23,368
that investing in Toys R Us

941
00:41:23,428 --> 00:41:26,168
and Blockbuster was a mistake on my part,
the fact

942
00:41:26,168 --> 00:41:29,448
that we continue to invest billions of
dollars into research

943
00:41:29,448 --> 00:41:30,568
that isn't applicable

944
00:41:30,568 --> 00:41:33,968
to human beings is blowing my mind. How
does this happen?

945
00:41:34,598 --> 00:41:37,328
Unfortunately, animal research is big
business

946
00:41:37,478 --> 00:41:39,808
because we're not just talking about the
animals

947
00:41:39,958 --> 00:41:41,128
used in the lab.

948
00:41:41,348 --> 00:41:43,048
So there are major corporations

949
00:41:43,048 --> 00:41:46,448
that import, like, non-human primates
into the United States.

950
00:41:46,778 --> 00:41:49,848
There are major companies that breed dogs

951
00:41:49,988 --> 00:41:52,608
and other animals to be used in
experiments.

952
00:41:53,208 --> 00:41:55,328
Companies that create the cages, companies

953
00:41:55,328 --> 00:41:58,128
that create the restraining devices that
are used

954
00:41:58,128 --> 00:42:01,288
to restrain these animals when they're
being experimented on,

955
00:42:02,008 --> 00:42:03,168
companies that produce the food.

956
00:42:03,808 --> 00:42:05,728
A little black mouse could cost up

957
00:42:05,728 --> 00:42:07,608
to 30 US dollars. If you want a

958
00:42:07,928 --> 00:42:10,728
diabetic rat, it's around 500 US dollars

959
00:42:10,868 --> 00:42:11,928
to purchase from a company.

960
00:42:12,268 --> 00:42:13,728
And all these little instruments,

961
00:42:13,748 --> 00:42:16,288
can you think about having a little
catheter that needs

962
00:42:16,288 --> 00:42:17,488
to go into a mouse heart?

963
00:42:17,598 --> 00:42:19,768
Well, those cost thousands of dollars.

964
00:42:20,418 --> 00:42:23,888
Everything in animal research is
extremely expensive.

965
00:42:23,988 --> 00:42:26,568
And so you can imagine there's a lot of
business

966
00:42:26,588 --> 00:42:29,688
and corporate entities that want to hold
on

967
00:42:29,688 --> 00:42:30,848
to animal experimentation

968
00:42:30,848 --> 00:42:32,888
because that's how they make their money.

969
00:42:33,188 --> 00:42:35,328
If you go to any public meeting

970
00:42:35,758 --> 00:42:39,568
that a government agency holds about a
non-animal test

971
00:42:39,568 --> 00:42:40,888
method is being considered

972
00:42:40,908 --> 00:42:42,848
as a replacement for an animal method...

973
00:42:42,848 --> 00:42:47,688
Representatives from contract research
organizations attend,

974
00:42:48,068 --> 00:42:51,488
and they also bring attorneys with the
express purpose

975
00:42:52,188 --> 00:42:53,288
of making sure

976
00:42:53,468 --> 00:42:55,968
and keeping a given animal test in place

977
00:42:56,198 --> 00:42:57,368
that that's preserved.

978
00:42:58,208 --> 00:42:59,768
I wish I had this sort of lobbying power

979
00:42:59,828 --> 00:43:01,248
for my own financial interests.

980
00:43:01,728 --> 00:43:03,968
Industry influencing policy is an old
story,

981
00:43:04,268 --> 00:43:06,728
but we don't always get to see everyone
that they impact.

982
00:43:07,028 --> 00:43:10,848
So this is Samson. Samson is an
8-year-old male beagle.

983
00:43:11,268 --> 00:43:14,768
He was rescued 11 days ago from a

984
00:43:15,518 --> 00:43:19,488
5,000 dog breeding mill in the United
States

985
00:43:20,318 --> 00:43:22,688
that raises beagles

986
00:43:22,788 --> 00:43:26,488
and sells them to laboratories for use in
experiments.

987
00:43:26,598 --> 00:43:29,528
They sell them to the National Institutes
of Health.

988
00:43:29,838 --> 00:43:31,288
They sell them to universities,

989
00:43:31,628 --> 00:43:35,048
and they sell them to contract research
organizations

990
00:43:35,268 --> 00:43:36,968
that experiment on these animals.

991
00:43:37,508 --> 00:43:39,448
Samson was born at this facility

992
00:43:40,068 --> 00:43:43,408
and until 10 days ago, he'd never seen a
bed.

993
00:43:44,278 --> 00:43:46,488
He'd probably never put his paws on grass,

994
00:43:47,078 --> 00:43:50,248
largely been housed alone for all eight
years

995
00:43:50,268 --> 00:43:51,848
of his so-called life to that point.

996
00:43:52,268 --> 00:43:55,448
So Samson was primarily a breeding
animal.

997
00:43:55,708 --> 00:43:58,728
And the records at this facility where he
was kept show

998
00:43:59,548 --> 00:44:04,008
his breeding produced, so to speak, about
200 puppies.

999
00:44:04,978 --> 00:44:08,048
Those animals are each sold for hundreds

1000
00:44:08,048 --> 00:44:09,728
and hundreds of dollars, if not more.

1001
00:44:09,728 --> 00:44:12,328
And so over the course of his eight years,

1002
00:44:13,148 --> 00:44:16,288
he made this company likely a hundred
thousand dollars.

1003
00:44:17,338 --> 00:44:19,128
After spending some time with Samson,

1004
00:44:19,568 --> 00:44:21,368
I wondered if the sale of his puppies

1005
00:44:21,368 --> 00:44:22,928
to laboratories made enough money

1006
00:44:22,988 --> 00:44:24,768
for everyone involved to sleep at night.

1007
00:44:25,718 --> 00:44:28,168
With so much money going into animal
research

1008
00:44:28,168 --> 00:44:29,888
and testing, I knew to look

1009
00:44:29,888 --> 00:44:31,528
for lobbying power coming out of it.

1010
00:44:31,868 --> 00:44:34,328
It turns out that this industry is so
powerful,

1011
00:44:34,468 --> 00:44:35,968
it can actually shape laws.

1012
00:44:36,188 --> 00:44:37,728
That's when I learned about the Animal

1013
00:44:37,728 --> 00:44:39,128
Enterprise Terrorism Act.

1014
00:44:39,648 --> 00:44:41,168
Delci Winders, a legal scholar

1015
00:44:41,168 --> 00:44:43,888
