to help people like him

1257
00:54:23,508 --> 00:54:25,568
or the guy who was sitting next to his bed

1258
00:54:25,788 --> 00:54:27,768
or everybody in that cardiac ward.

1259
00:54:28,588 --> 00:54:30,208
My research was never going

1260
00:54:30,228 --> 00:54:32,168
to make a difference for people like that.

1261
00:54:32,598 --> 00:54:33,928
That is not sentimental.

1262
00:54:34,108 --> 00:54:36,768
That's using my judgment as a scientist

1263
00:54:36,828 --> 00:54:38,088
to do something different.

1264
00:54:38,278 --> 00:54:40,168
This is how our culture evolved.

1265
00:54:40,488 --> 00:54:42,928
I carried out animal testing pretty much
throughout my

1266
00:54:42,928 --> 00:54:44,888
life, like, the bulk part of my life up

1267
00:54:44,888 --> 00:54:46,168
to the middle of my PhD.

1268
00:54:46,718 --> 00:54:47,888
That is when I started

1269
00:54:47,988 --> 00:54:50,248
to think "maybe this whole thing isn't
right."

1270
00:54:50,628 --> 00:54:52,328
All the professors, all my colleagues,

1271
00:54:52,328 --> 00:54:54,488
all my fellow students, they're all doing
this.

1272
00:54:54,948 --> 00:54:56,928
It cannot be wrong.

1273
00:54:57,548 --> 00:54:59,128
So I went to my committee meeting

1274
00:54:59,388 --> 00:55:01,488
and then one professor told me, "don't
think about it."

1275
00:55:02,068 --> 00:55:03,728
"Get your head down, finish your research,

1276
00:55:03,728 --> 00:55:05,328
publish your research and get out.

1277
00:55:05,848 --> 00:55:07,608
Graduate. You know, this is not something

1278
00:55:07,608 --> 00:55:08,768
that you should be concerned about."

1279
00:55:08,958 --> 00:55:10,568
Like, just, she straight up said that.

1280
00:55:10,708 --> 00:55:13,568
That's when I decided that I'm not going
to do this anymore.

1281
00:55:14,348 --> 00:55:16,728
For my thesis, in the front, there was a
line:

1282
00:55:16,988 --> 00:55:18,528
"For all the animals that I have killed.

1283
00:55:18,708 --> 00:55:22,648
I'm sorry. I was wrong." My thesis
advisor told me

1284
00:55:22,648 --> 00:55:24,888
that if I put that in, it will jeopardize

1285
00:55:24,948 --> 00:55:26,128
my chance of graduation.

1286
00:55:26,988 --> 00:55:29,448
But let the record show that I intended to

1287
00:55:30,038 --> 00:55:32,968
acknowledge the animals, um, that I've
harmed and killed.

1288
00:55:34,828 --> 00:55:36,568
Dr. Cheng's story reminded me

1289
00:55:36,568 --> 00:55:39,168
that inefficiency in the lab isn't why a
majority

1290
00:55:39,168 --> 00:55:41,208
of Americans disapprove of animal testing

1291
00:55:41,868 --> 00:55:44,808
or why some people protest the places
that do it.

1292
00:55:44,808 --> 00:55:47,048
What did you see that moved you so much?

1293
00:55:47,668 --> 00:55:49,008
During this brief period of time

1294
00:55:49,008 --> 00:55:50,568
that the undercover investigator was

1295
00:55:50,588 --> 00:55:52,328
inside the laboratory in New Jersey,

1296
00:55:53,108 --> 00:55:57,648
she documented horrific cruelty,
including the live necropsy

1297
00:55:58,068 --> 00:56:01,968
of a primate without anesthetic on a
table.

1298
00:56:03,188 --> 00:56:07,328
Its entire torso opened up, ribcage
opened up,

1299
00:56:07,378 --> 00:56:12,048
heart still beating, and the being tried
to snap

1300
00:56:12,708 --> 00:56:17,048
and bite the people that were cutting her
apart.

1301
00:56:17,268 --> 00:56:21,008
And while doing so, one of the
technicians said something

1302
00:56:21,008 --> 00:56:22,808
to the extent of, "you wanna f***in' bite
me?"

1303
00:56:23,418 --> 00:56:25,248
"Let's dance, b***h! Let's dance!"

1304
00:56:25,948 --> 00:56:27,688
And was chastising

1305
00:56:27,688 --> 00:56:29,808
and like making fun of this animal

1306
00:56:29,808 --> 00:56:31,608
that they were cutting apart alive.

1307
00:56:32,028 --> 00:56:35,048
And I just saw that and I'm like, how
does this exist?

1308
00:56:35,788 --> 00:56:37,768
And so they say that we're extreme, right?

1309
00:56:39,708 --> 00:56:43,768
My actions, dubbed extremism, pale in
comparison

1310
00:56:43,908 --> 00:56:47,808
to cutting apart a creature on a table,
making fun of it

1311
00:56:47,868 --> 00:56:50,568
as you take its life from them, without
anesthetic,

1312
00:56:51,268 --> 00:56:52,808
as it convulses on this table.

1313
00:56:54,748 --> 00:56:56,968
The dogs repeatedly getting punched in
the face.

1314
00:56:57,858 --> 00:57:01,808
These are not isolated incidents when you
have a laboratory

1315
00:57:01,908 --> 00:57:05,288
in Occold, England where there's a hidden
camera going

1316
00:57:05,748 --> 00:57:07,768
and a laboratory in East Millstone, New
Jersey

1317
00:57:08,298 --> 00:57:09,408
where a camera's going,

1318
00:57:09,788 --> 00:57:11,648
and for the brief period of time

1319
00:57:11,648 --> 00:57:14,048
that those reporters were in there,
couple of weeks here

1320
00:57:14,228 --> 00:57:16,928
and a couple of weeks there, that they
get this trove

1321
00:57:16,928 --> 00:57:18,528
of evidence that shows this?

1322
00:57:18,988 --> 00:57:20,808
It doesn't show that these are outliers.

1323
00:57:21,148 --> 00:57:23,368
It doesn't show that there's a couple of
bad apples.

1324
00:57:23,508 --> 00:57:25,808
It shows that the whole orchard is rotten.

1325
00:57:29,168 --> 00:57:31,008
Occasionally, you'll see some really
troubling footage,

1326
00:57:31,228 --> 00:57:33,848
and we certainly would never say that

1327
00:57:34,028 --> 00:57:37,048
um, everybody involved in biomedical
research is a hundred

1328
00:57:37,248 --> 00:57:38,648
percent perfect a hundred percent of the
time.

1329
00:57:38,938 --> 00:57:40,368
There are some bad actors

1330
00:57:40,548 --> 00:57:43,968
and unfortunately, um, you know, when an
infiltration occurs

1331
00:57:43,968 --> 00:57:47,088
and they show the bad actors, um,
unfortunately

1332
00:57:47,088 --> 00:57:49,448
that's portrayed as being the standard
situation.

1333
00:57:50,008 --> 00:57:51,688
I will tell you from working in a
research setting,

1334
00:57:51,808 --> 00:57:54,128
I have never seen somebody mistreat an
animal in my,

1335
00:57:54,388 --> 00:57:57,768
you know, 15 or so years working in a
primate facility,

1336
00:57:57,768 --> 00:57:59,048
working in other facilities,

1337
00:57:59,348 --> 00:58:02,008
and it disgusts me when I, when I see an
image like that,

1338
00:58:02,428 --> 00:58:05,328
um, that is not the norm and nor should
it be

1339
00:58:05,548 --> 00:58:06,888
and certainly the laws

1340
00:58:06,888 --> 00:58:09,168
and regulations that exist should be used
in those cases.

1341
00:58:10,698 --> 00:58:12,528
Reassuring though it was to imagine

1342
00:58:12,528 --> 00:58:14,848
that I could work in research for over a
decade

1343
00:58:15,028 --> 00:58:17,208
and never witness the mistreatment of an
animal,

1344
00:58:17,748 --> 00:58:19,768
it didn't match with the other stories I
was hearing.

1345
00:58:20,528 --> 00:58:21,768
I decided to meet with Dr.

1346
00:58:21,838 --> 00:58:24,648
John Gluck, a psychologist who worked on
monkeys

1347
00:58:24,648 --> 00:58:26,248
in laboratories for most of his career

1348
00:58:26,668 --> 00:58:29,368
before deciding to instead study
bioethics.

1349
00:58:29,768 --> 00:58:33,928
I can't imagine somebody really heavily
experienced in

1350
00:58:34,068 --> 00:58:37,488
animal labs who could say they've never
seen anything.

1351
00:58:37,768 --> 00:58:41,008
I think what people probably mean when
they say

1352
00:58:41,008 --> 00:58:43,768
they haven't seen mistreatment is they
haven't seen,

1353
00:58:44,548 --> 00:58:46,288
you know, monkeys being punched

1354
00:58:46,588 --> 00:58:50,488
or gratuitously exposed to painful stimuli

1355
00:58:50,488 --> 00:58:51,768
and so on and so forth.

1356
00:58:52,058 --> 00:58:54,888
You'd have to have a pretty narrow
definition of

1357
00:58:54,918 --> 00:58:57,168
what "mistreatment" means to say

1358
00:58:57,448 --> 00:59:01,648
"I haven't seen it." A lot of just the
basic things that we do

1359
00:59:01,648 --> 00:59:04,528
to animals in laboratories are
mistreatment.

1360
00:59:05,048 --> 00:59:07,928
I think we're, we're fooling ourselves if
we

1361
00:59:07,928 --> 00:59:09,168
say we've never seen it.

1362
00:59:13,188 --> 00:59:16,168
So this is Gizmo. He's a long-tail
macaque.

1363
00:59:17,188 --> 00:59:21,048
He was used in animal experimentation. As
with all

1364
00:59:21,128 --> 00:59:22,888
of the monkeys who come to us from labs,

1365
00:59:23,228 --> 00:59:26,528
we don't know his backstory. They come to
us as this kind

1366
00:59:26,528 --> 00:59:29,368
of unknown. Unknown trauma has happened

1367
00:59:29,368 --> 00:59:31,448
to them at some stage. He

1368
00:59:31,448 --> 00:59:33,848
and his group all came to us with their
restraint collars on.

1369
00:59:34,108 --> 00:59:36,128
We can guess some of the types

1370
00:59:36,148 --> 00:59:37,328
of things that were done to them.

1371
00:59:37,328 --> 00:59:39,048
They weren't used in behavioral studies.

1372
00:59:39,198 --> 00:59:42,968
They were at some stage restrained, which
points

1373
00:59:43,108 --> 00:59:44,288
to invasive studies.

1374
00:59:44,748 --> 00:59:48,448
We had one monkey called Theo, who has
now passed away,

1375
00:59:48,468 --> 00:59:50,088
who came to us from a laboratory.

1376
00:59:50,508 --> 00:59:51,928
He had recurring eye problems

1377
00:59:51,928 --> 00:59:53,208
that we just couldn't get to the bottom
of.

1378
00:59:53,208 --> 00:59:55,608
We, we could tell that he was struggling
with his eyesight,

1379
00:59:55,608 --> 00:59:57,728
but every exam, his eyes looked perfectly
normal.

1380
00:59:58,348 --> 01:00:00,368
So we ended up taking him to a specialist,

1381
01:00:00,508 --> 01:00:02,768
and what they found was that a six inch
piece

1382
01:00:02,768 --> 01:00:04,408
of wire had been left in his skull.

1383
01:00:05,688 --> 01:00:08,568
Laboratories talk about retiring monkeys
as if they've kind

1384
01:00:08,568 --> 01:00:10,808
of lived this full life and had this
working life,

1385
01:00:10,828 --> 01:00:12,328
and then they choose to kind of give it up

1386
01:00:12,328 --> 01:00:14,128
to go, you know, go and live in Florida.

1387
01:00:14,388 --> 01:00:17,928
But they come to us and they're
traumatized.

1388
01:00:18,068 --> 01:00:19,848
You know, some of them have been tortured.

1389
01:00:19,868 --> 01:00:21,928
At the very least they've been socially
isolated,

1390
01:00:22,348 --> 01:00:24,888
and sanctuary isn't a happy ending.

1391
01:00:25,368 --> 01:00:28,648
Sanctuary is a really difficult journey

1392
01:00:28,908 --> 01:00:30,408
for all of them.

1393
01:00:30,948 --> 01:00:32,208
All of these answers brought up an

1394
01:00:32,208 --> 01:00:33,248
important question for me.

1395
01:00:33,998 --> 01:00:35,288
What is the state of laws

1396
01:00:35,288 --> 01:00:37,688
and regulations around cruelty in
laboratories?

1397
01:00:38,208 --> 01:00:40,488
I met with Deborah Press, a legal expert

1398
01:00:40,588 --> 01:00:42,248
and former USDA inspector.

1399
01:00:42,588 --> 01:00:45,528
And the Animal Welfare Act is more
remarkable for

1400
01:00:46,238 --> 01:00:48,248
what it doesn't do than for what it does.

1401
01:00:48,478 --> 01:00:51,928
Lots of cruelty is conducted by, by
plenty of Animal Welfare

1402
01:00:52,548 --> 01:00:56,968
Act regulated businesses. You know,
experiments forcing dogs

1403
01:00:57,228 --> 01:01:00,648
to run on treadmills until their hearts
give out.

1404
01:01:00,748 --> 01:01:04,048
So much of this is legal under the Animal
Welfare Act.

1405
01:01:04,178 --> 01:01:06,448
There are a lot of good inspectors at USDA

1406
01:01:06,478 --> 01:01:08,688
that are veterinarians that do a really
good job.

1407
01:01:09,108 --> 01:01:11,568
We just saw this recently where hundreds

1408
01:01:11,708 --> 01:01:14,288
of beagles were being bred for animal
research,

1409
01:01:14,588 --> 01:01:16,408
and they did an undercover investigation.

1410
01:01:16,788 --> 01:01:19,528
The USDA inspectors kept telling their
higher ups

1411
01:01:19,558 --> 01:01:21,448
that it was a terrible situation, that
they needed

1412
01:01:21,448 --> 01:01:22,608
to go back more, that they needed

1413
01:01:22,608 --> 01:01:23,768
to bring in more inspectors,

1414
01:01:23,768 --> 01:01:26,968
and the higher up said no, you, optics
would be bad-

1415
01:01:26,968 --> 01:01:31,208
The optics would be bad for saving dogs
from rampant cruelty?

1416
01:01:31,688 --> 01:01:33,568
Shocking, right? Who are the optics bad
for?

1417
01:01:33,568 --> 01:01:35,448
They're bad for the research institution.

1418
01:01:36,008 --> 01:01:38,768
USDA doesn't want to look like they're
doing too much.

1419
01:01:38,878 --> 01:01:40,288
They don't wanna look like they're

1420
01:01:40,888 --> 01:01:43,528
bringing down the hammer on the entities
that they regulate.

1421
01:01:43,708 --> 01:01:45,048
We just see time and time again,

1422
01:01:45,048 --> 01:01:46,288
the enforcement isn't there.

1423
01:01:46,288 --> 01:01:48,888
They're not gonna stand up to industry.

1424
01:01:49,018 --> 01:01:52,968
There has only ever been a single
criminal prosecution

1425
01:01:53,308 --> 01:01:56,008
of an animal experimenter in the United
States,

1426
01:01:56,828 --> 01:01:59,368
and that conviction was overturned

1427
01:01:59,388 --> 01:02:00,448
by the state Supreme Court.

1428
01:02:01,888 --> 01:02:04,368
I had to hope, to wonder if the kind

1429
01:02:04,368 --> 01:02:05,648
of cruelty being described

1430
01:02:05,648 --> 01:02:08,328
to me was something from a bygone era of
research.

1431
01:02:08,598 --> 01:02:10,368
Then I spoke to someone who was working

1432
01:02:10,468 --> 01:02:12,728
for a laboratory at the time of our
interview,

1433
01:02:13,068 --> 01:02:14,168
an interview they agreed

1434
01:02:14,168 --> 01:02:16,088
to only on the condition of anonymity.

1435
01:02:17,038 --> 01:02:19,168
What is life like for the animals in your
work?

1436
01:02:20,038 --> 01:02:22,168
Usually the animals are kept in crowded,

1437
01:02:22,758 --> 01:02:23,808
unclean conditions.

1438
01:02:24,438 --> 01:02:27,008
Some are bred to have debilitating
illnesses

1439
01:02:27,108 --> 01:02:28,648
or given purposeful injuries.

1440
01:02:28,918 --> 01:02:30,088
I've seen illnesses

1441
01:02:30,188 --> 01:02:32,248
and injuries that were unrelated

1442
01:02:32,248 --> 01:02:34,568
to the research be ignored, supposedly

1443
01:02:34,718 --> 01:02:36,928
because treatment may interfere with
results.

1444
01:02:37,518 --> 01:02:40,088
I've also seen animals suffer and die

1445
01:02:40,088 --> 01:02:43,128
because they were denied proper food,
water, or help.

1446
01:02:43,438 --> 01:02:47,088
I've seen animals too paralyzed to drag
themselves to food.

1447
01:02:47,838 --> 01:02:49,568
Some with ulcerated eyes

1448
01:02:49,748 --> 01:02:52,728
or weeping skin wounds, prolapsed organs.

1449
01:02:53,348 --> 01:02:55,048
It has been traumatic to witness.

1450
01:02:57,568 --> 01:02:59,088
I wanted to explore the science

1451
01:02:59,108 --> 01:03:00,648
behind the medicines we take.

1452
01:03:01,808 --> 01:03:04,528
I really did not want to look at what
happens to the animals

1453
01:03:04,588 --> 01:03:07,248
inside of these places, but

1454
01:03:07,318 --> 01:03:10,048
with everything I was learning, how could
I not look?

1455
01:03:11,668 --> 01:03:15,928
The physical brutality, the cruelty is
hard to look at.

1456
01:03:16,788 --> 01:03:21,608
It is ugly and it is nauseating.

1457
01:03:21,818 --> 01:03:24,328
For me, there is a greater, existential
nausea

1458
01:03:24,558 --> 01:03:27,528
that comes not from looking at the
technician punching a

1459
01:03:27,528 --> 01:03:29,888
beagle or the scientist dissecting a

1460
01:03:29,888 --> 01:03:31,128
primate without an anesthesia.

1461
01:03:31,798 --> 01:03:34,448
It's the people around them who don't
interfere,

1462
01:03:35,228 --> 01:03:38,208
who don't write reports, who circle the
wagons

1463
01:03:38,208 --> 01:03:40,728
and pull out a checkbook to make the
problem disappear

1464
01:03:41,028 --> 01:03:42,688
and act like we're all doing our best.

1465
01:03:44,268 --> 01:03:46,768
The lobbyists who write impunity into the
law

1466
01:03:47,588 --> 01:03:50,408
and the people like me who don't want to
look

1467
01:03:50,798 --> 01:03:53,888
because it is so uncomfortable to see

1468
01:03:53,888 --> 01:03:57,368
what is done in my name. How does this
continue?

1469
01:04:00,118 --> 01:04:02,128
When I was in college, we were studying
psychology.

1470
01:04:02,488 --> 01:04:05,608
I remember I was putting some electrodes
into the brain

1471
01:04:05,608 --> 01:04:07,888
of a white rat that had been given to me
by my professor,

1472
01:04:08,668 --> 01:04:11,208
and we had to put them in a stereotactic
device,

1473
01:04:11,298 --> 01:04:12,648
which is like a metal pencil

1474
01:04:12,958 --> 01:04:14,848
that goes into this ear and into this ear.

1475
01:04:15,108 --> 01:04:17,608
And as I put this rat in the stereotactic
device

1476
01:04:18,028 --> 01:04:21,248
and I turned the little thumbscrews at
one point I heard "thk,

1477
01:04:21,388 --> 01:04:25,048
thk" and I said to my professor, I said,
"I,

1478
01:04:25,128 --> 01:04:26,968
I think I just went through his eardrums."

1479
01:04:28,228 --> 01:04:30,768
And he said, "perfect. That's where you
wanna be.

1480
01:04:30,768 --> 01:04:32,168
That'll hold his skull really tight."

1481
01:04:32,768 --> 01:04:35,488
I said, "but wait a minute. You know,
doesn't that hurt?"

1482
01:04:36,068 --> 01:04:38,728
He said "he wasn't gonna listen to his
stereo tomorrow anyway."

1483
01:04:38,948 --> 01:04:42,648
This was a kind man. He was a nice guy.

1484
01:04:43,388 --> 01:04:47,888
But I realized that somehow his culture

1485
01:04:48,068 --> 01:04:50,888
of being in science made him miss the
most obvious things,

1486
01:04:50,888 --> 01:04:52,808
which is animals feel pain.

1487
01:04:53,748 --> 01:04:55,928
And frankly, there was no point to what
we were doing.

1488
01:04:56,558 --> 01:04:59,008
Most people, they just get desensitized

1489
01:04:59,148 --> 01:05:00,528
enough to carry out the work.

1490
01:05:01,068 --> 01:05:04,648
But then in their mind, deep down,

1491
01:05:05,358 --> 01:05:07,848
they're battling that oppression

1492
01:05:08,198 --> 01:05:09,248
because you're trying

1493
01:05:09,248 --> 01:05:12,128
to intentionally inflict diseases and pain

1494
01:05:12,128 --> 01:05:13,728
and distress in animals

1495
01:05:13,748 --> 01:05:16,888
and eventually killing them without
affecting your work.

1496
01:05:17,668 --> 01:05:19,128
So that is a constant battle

1497
01:05:19,668 --> 01:05:22,608
and we, we know that PTSD is a real thing

1498
01:05:22,708 --> 01:05:24,488
for ex animal experimenters.

1499
01:05:24,628 --> 01:05:26,568
And we see this in the veterinary field.

1500
01:05:26,568 --> 01:05:28,008
We see this in slaughterhouse workers.

1501
01:05:28,508 --> 01:05:30,528
Animal experimenters are not exceptions.

1502
01:05:31,868 --> 01:05:35,488
We are the human victims In the animal
testing world.

1503
01:05:37,718 --> 01:05:41,008
It's hard to find people who, who love
people

1504
01:05:41,028 --> 01:05:42,528
and animals so strongly

1505
01:05:42,958 --> 01:05:45,048
that they can actually do that for years
and years.

1506
01:05:45,068 --> 01:05:46,568
And so they need support. And I,

1507
01:05:46,808 --> 01:05:47,928
I feel very strongly about this.

1508
01:05:48,008 --> 01:05:49,928
I think our community has not done nearly
enough

1509
01:05:49,948 --> 01:05:51,128
to support them properly.

1510
01:05:51,558 --> 01:05:54,648
They really need to evaluate the nature
of this, uh,

1511
01:05:54,648 --> 01:05:55,808
you call it compassion fatigue.

1512
01:05:55,908 --> 01:05:57,048
I'm not crazy about that term,

1513
01:05:57,108 --> 01:06:00,168
but the nature of that, uh, for our folks
is not the same

1514
01:06:00,168 --> 01:06:03,048
as it is for an ICU nurse, you know,
who's just trying

1515
01:06:03,048 --> 01:06:04,408
to take care of a very sick patient

1516
01:06:04,788 --> 01:06:07,168
or a veterinarian who gets a very sick
animal

1517
01:06:07,168 --> 01:06:08,248
and has to put the animal down.

1518
01:06:08,248 --> 01:06:10,088
You know, our people are sometimes tasked
with

1519
01:06:10,688 --> 01:06:13,648
euthanizing animals who are, you know,
for the most part

1520
01:06:13,648 --> 01:06:14,888
healthy, because the study's over.

1521
01:06:14,898 --> 01:06:16,528
These are animals they cared for directly

1522
01:06:16,528 --> 01:06:17,768
that they then have to euthanize.

1523
01:06:18,108 --> 01:06:20,848
And it's been likened to something that's
more similar to

1524
01:06:20,848 --> 01:06:23,928
what, um, war veterans would go through,
right?

1525
01:06:23,988 --> 01:06:25,288
You know, they're, they're in

1526
01:06:25,288 --> 01:06:26,648
a situation where they know they're doing
the right thing.

1527
01:06:26,648 --> 01:06:27,968
They're defending their country and you
know,

1528
01:06:27,968 --> 01:06:29,288
in this, in this example, right?

1529
01:06:29,388 --> 01:06:31,848
But maybe they have to kill women and
children

1530
01:06:31,848 --> 01:06:34,688
because the circumstances become very
dangerous

1531
01:06:34,688 --> 01:06:36,088
and dictate that. They have to...

1532
01:06:36,308 --> 01:06:38,848
That's not the- it's a very different
kind of struggle.

1533
01:06:40,598 --> 01:06:44,608
What the f**k? Do we have to kill women
and children?

1534
01:06:45,188 --> 01:06:49,608
Is that necessary? And I don't, I mean,

1535
01:06:50,528 --> 01:06:52,808
I expected to hear that kind of
comparison from someone

1536
01:06:52,828 --> 01:06:56,768
who works for PETA, not from someone
who's an advocate

1537
01:06:56,768 --> 01:06:58,048
for doing research on animals.

1538
01:06:59,188 --> 01:07:01,208
Is the fight against disease like a war?

1539
01:07:01,708 --> 01:07:04,328
And is it good for scientists to see
themselves as soldiers?

1540
01:07:04,758 --> 01:07:08,528
When a student in our lab says, "I'm

1541
01:07:09,168 --> 01:07:12,248
squeamish about what you're asking me to
do to these animals

1542
01:07:12,348 --> 01:07:15,168
as part of my experiment," what are we
likely to say?

1543
01:07:15,518 --> 01:07:18,328
"Well, maybe you're not built for this
profession."

1544
01:07:18,548 --> 01:07:21,968
So maybe you're just too wimpy

1545
01:07:23,308 --> 01:07:24,488
to deal with the truth.

1546
01:07:25,028 --> 01:07:27,648
In other words, shut up.

1547
01:07:27,988 --> 01:07:31,368
So that's what we're telling those people
when we tell them

1548
01:07:31,398 --> 01:07:32,688
that their concerns

1549
01:07:32,788 --> 01:07:35,528
or their sensitivities are irrelevant,

1550
01:07:36,058 --> 01:07:37,888
we're saying just toughen up.

1551
01:07:38,398 --> 01:07:42,088
Just like being in bootcamp. The model of
I'm a soldier

1552
01:07:42,758 --> 01:07:44,168
just doesn't work for me.

1553
01:07:45,048 --> 01:07:47,648
I know something about being insensitive,
dismissive,

1554
01:07:47,668 --> 01:07:49,408
and attached to an old way of thinking.

1555
01:07:49,778 --> 01:07:51,928
Until I got older and saw more of the
world,

1556
01:07:52,528 --> 01:07:55,048
I thought Great Britain was a myth used
to scare children.

1557
01:07:55,648 --> 01:07:58,128
Nevertheless, even though I could
appreciate

1558
01:07:58,128 --> 01:07:59,528
that animal research and testing

1559
01:07:59,668 --> 01:08:02,688
in best case scenarios still yields
useful information,

1560
01:08:03,508 --> 01:08:04,888
it was increasingly clear

1561
01:08:04,888 --> 01:08:07,208
that this system isn't meaningfully
regulated,

1562
01:08:07,478 --> 01:08:10,088
that it abides unbelievable cruelty above

1563
01:08:10,088 --> 01:08:12,288
and beyond the already upsetting
experiments

1564
01:08:12,788 --> 01:08:14,368
and that an unconscionable amount

1565
01:08:14,388 --> 01:08:17,128
of the experimentation going on with
animals today

1566
01:08:17,638 --> 01:08:21,168
doesn't fit into that category of
lifesaving and necessary.

1567
01:08:22,438 --> 01:08:23,888
Over the course of these interviews,

1568
01:08:24,048 --> 01:08:25,288
I had heard about alternatives

1569
01:08:25,288 --> 01:08:28,048
to animal experiments like computer
processing,

1570
01:08:28,278 --> 01:08:30,408
cell cultures, non-invasive imaging,

1571
01:08:30,748 --> 01:08:32,768
and 3D bioprinting human tissue.

1572
01:08:33,348 --> 01:08:35,888
One of the most impressive new
alternatives is called an

1573
01:08:35,888 --> 01:08:38,008
"organ on a chip," which sounded like a
cross

1574
01:08:38,008 --> 01:08:40,568
between something from Star Trek and an
hors d'oeuvre.

1575
01:08:40,708 --> 01:08:43,368
So I visited Emulate, a company in Boston

1576
01:08:43,478 --> 01:08:45,168
that develops them, to learn more.

1577
01:08:45,548 --> 01:08:50,208
An organ on a chip is a small device that
allows you

1578
01:08:50,268 --> 01:08:52,168
to culture human cells.

1579
01:08:52,228 --> 01:08:55,208
So these are usually taken from a biopsy
of a patient

1580
01:08:55,348 --> 01:08:56,968
and it allows these cells to grow in

1581
01:08:57,108 --> 01:08:59,368
and form tissues like they do in the body.

1582
01:08:59,508 --> 01:09:00,568
And so that's relevant

1583
01:09:00,568 --> 01:09:03,608
because alternatives, using animal tissues

1584
01:09:04,268 --> 01:09:06,888
or using systems that don't provide flow

1585
01:09:06,988 --> 01:09:09,128
or stretching, they're, they're lacking a
lot of

1586
01:09:09,128 --> 01:09:10,528
that physiologic relevance.

1587
01:09:10,548 --> 01:09:13,008
And so you're able to test any drug that
you want

1588
01:09:13,008 --> 01:09:15,448
to introduce into the system and also
different cell types.

1589
01:09:15,868 --> 01:09:19,368
We just published a large study in a
nature portfolio

1590
01:09:19,368 --> 01:09:21,088
journal called Communications Medicine,

1591
01:09:21,708 --> 01:09:24,208
and in this study we tested 27 different

1592
01:09:24,728 --> 01:09:26,448
compounds on our liver chip

1593
01:09:26,468 --> 01:09:29,368
to see if they cause drug induced liver
injury.

1594
01:09:29,418 --> 01:09:31,648
These were a known set of compounds that
had gone

1595
01:09:31,648 --> 01:09:33,448
through animal in vivo testing,

1596
01:09:34,028 --> 01:09:35,928
had gone into human clinical trials.

1597
01:09:36,228 --> 01:09:38,528
So we had animal data and human data.

1598
01:09:39,348 --> 01:09:42,368
Of those drugs, 22 of them were deemed
hepatotoxic

1599
01:09:42,588 --> 01:09:44,408
by the FDA classification.

1600
01:09:45,508 --> 01:09:48,688
All 22 of those were missed by animals

1601
01:09:48,868 --> 01:09:50,208
and went into clinical trials.

1602
01:09:51,068 --> 01:09:54,728
Our liver chip was able to detect 87% of
those

1603
01:09:54,918 --> 01:09:57,008
that were missed by animals.

1604
01:09:57,038 --> 01:09:59,448
Looking at the history of these drugs, um,

1605
01:09:59,908 --> 01:10:03,048
of the 22, 2 were stopped in clinical
trials

1606
01:10:03,048 --> 01:10:04,488
because of patient fatalities.

1607
01:10:05,128 --> 01:10:06,448
Patients unfortunately passed away.

1608
01:10:07,508 --> 01:10:10,248
10 of them ended up making it to market

1609
01:10:10,388 --> 01:10:13,128
and then being pulled off the market
post-approval

1610
01:10:13,128 --> 01:10:15,688
because of drug induced liver injury
effects that occurred

1611
01:10:15,738 --> 01:10:17,448
after market approval.

1612
01:10:17,788 --> 01:10:19,768
And so this is the first data

1613
01:10:19,978 --> 01:10:22,368
where you have truth in animal in vivo,

1614
01:10:22,698 --> 01:10:24,608
truth in human in vivo,

1615
01:10:24,908 --> 01:10:26,768
and then, how did the chip perform?

1616
01:10:27,158 --> 01:10:28,888
It's the perfect data set to do so.

1617
01:10:29,038 --> 01:10:31,328
Yeah, we've developed something like 15

1618
01:10:31,328 --> 01:10:32,368
different organ chips.

1619
01:10:32,378 --> 01:10:34,328
We've done kidney, we've done intestine,

1620
01:10:34,328 --> 01:10:36,088
we've done the different parts of the
intestine,

1621
01:10:36,108 --> 01:10:38,048
the duodenum, ileum, jejunum, the colon.

1622
01:10:38,098 --> 01:10:40,328
We've done different parts of the lung,
the airway

1623
01:10:40,388 --> 01:10:41,728
and the air sac.

1624
01:10:41,728 --> 01:10:44,728
Lung on a chip, kidney on a chip, liver
on a chip,

1625
01:10:44,968 --> 01:10:47,408
A human mini brain on a chip, a gut on a
chip,

1626
01:10:47,568 --> 01:10:48,688
a human nerve on a chip.

1627
01:10:48,798 --> 01:10:50,048
Just think about whatever organ

1628
01:10:50,228 --> 01:10:51,968
and somebody is probably working on that

1629
01:10:52,108 --> 01:10:53,728
And they're actually being connected now

1630
01:10:53,988 --> 01:10:55,768
to create the human body on a chip.

1631
01:10:55,878 --> 01:10:58,528
This is like a huge area of research that
helps

1632
01:10:58,548 --> 01:11:00,408
to eliminate animal models.

1633
01:11:00,998 --> 01:11:05,288
Here we show an example of putting all
the tubing together

1634
01:11:05,988 --> 01:11:10,328
of different organs to essentially go
towards creating

1635
01:11:10,328 --> 01:11:12,128
that human body on a chip.

1636
01:11:12,308 --> 01:11:15,488
In southern California, the Terasaki
Institute is not only

1637
01:11:15,488 --> 01:11:16,888
developing organs on a chip,

1638
01:11:17,158 --> 01:11:20,848
they're 3D bioprinting entire organs.
Human organs.

1639
01:11:21,108 --> 01:11:23,288
No mouse brains, no monkey business.

1640
01:11:23,628 --> 01:11:27,128
One of the things that 3D bioprinting is,

1641
01:11:27,128 --> 01:11:30,608
is really applying 3D printing concepts
to biological

1642
01:11:31,208 --> 01:11:32,848
materials and tissues.

1643
01:11:32,878 --> 01:11:34,608
There's lots of different applications
that you could do

1644
01:11:34,918 --> 01:11:39,168
with this type of 3D bioprinter if you're
using it

1645
01:11:39,348 --> 01:11:40,728
to model disease.

1646
01:11:41,148 --> 01:11:44,928
If you want to, let's say make a cancer
model, you know,

1647
01:11:44,928 --> 01:11:47,288
you could print a pancreas, you could put
cancer cells

1648
01:11:47,288 --> 01:11:50,808
inside and then that would allow you to
have something

1649
01:11:50,808 --> 01:11:55,168
to test your drug therapies on instead of
an animal model.

1650
01:11:55,748 --> 01:11:59,208
So being able to build tissues in three
dimensions

1651
01:11:59,588 --> 01:12:02,488
and be able to use the cells of a, let's
say,

1652
01:12:02,488 --> 01:12:03,648
individual patient

1653
01:12:04,148 --> 01:12:07,688
and understand how that patient tissue
responds

1654
01:12:07,868 --> 01:12:10,248
to a particular drug is gonna be really
important.

1655
01:12:10,268 --> 01:12:13,488
The reason I got into this field is
really for replacing

1656
01:12:14,038 --> 01:12:16,928
body parts for variety of different
diseases.

1657
01:12:16,938 --> 01:12:21,368
Right now there is a huge demand for
organs that can be used

1658
01:12:21,548 --> 01:12:22,568
for treating people

1659
01:12:22,788 --> 01:12:25,128
and it's really the reason why we do a lot

1660
01:12:25,128 --> 01:12:28,368
of this 3D bioprinting and tissue
engineering.

1661
01:12:28,788 --> 01:12:31,088
It does sound a little bit like science
fiction,

1662
01:12:31,628 --> 01:12:33,648
the distant future, but this is now.

1663
01:12:34,078 --> 01:12:35,648
It's been now for quite some time.

1664
01:12:35,648 --> 01:12:37,568
And the government is slowly catching up.

1665
01:12:38,108 --> 01:12:41,008
The recent passage of the FDA
Modernization ACT now allows

1666
01:12:41,008 --> 01:12:43,368
these cutting edge, human-relevant
alternatives

1667
01:12:43,368 --> 01:12:46,488
to be considered by the FDA instead of
animal data

1668
01:12:46,668 --> 01:12:48,688
as long as they can compete with animal
models.

1669
01:12:48,828 --> 01:12:50,528
And remember, animal models are often
terrible.

1670
01:12:50,948 --> 01:12:53,848
The FDA now will consider those results in

1671
01:12:53,848 --> 01:12:55,088
lieu of animal models.

1672
01:12:55,148 --> 01:12:56,528
So that's absolutely changing.

1673
01:12:56,728 --> 01:12:57,728
These methods

1674
01:12:57,728 --> 01:13:00,408
were a dream some 50 years ago,

1675
01:13:00,408 --> 01:13:03,008
but over the last, uh, 20, 30 years, more

1676
01:13:03,028 --> 01:13:05,288
and more of them have been introduced.

1677
01:13:05,598 --> 01:13:07,328
Some 50 methods are now available

1678
01:13:07,828 --> 01:13:09,888
for which we have international consensus

1679
01:13:09,888 --> 01:13:10,888
that they're doing the trick.

1680
01:13:11,308 --> 01:13:14,448
We were funded to respond to COVID using
our lung chips.

1681
01:13:14,508 --> 01:13:15,888
We came up with drugs that moved

1682
01:13:15,888 --> 01:13:17,328
to clinical trials within months.

1683
01:13:17,348 --> 01:13:19,048
We have other ones, at least in our
models,

1684
01:13:19,158 --> 01:13:21,488
prevent infection not only by SARS-CoV-2,

1685
01:13:21,488 --> 01:13:25,728
but the original SARS CoV, MERS, multiple
types of influenza.

1686
01:13:25,788 --> 01:13:27,728
To actually do- enable drug discovery,

1687
01:13:27,928 --> 01:13:29,888
I think is gonna transform drug
development.

1688
01:13:30,028 --> 01:13:33,208
And Dr. Chandrasekera's own Canadian
Centre for Alternatives

1689
01:13:33,208 --> 01:13:34,608
to Animal Methods is helping

1690
01:13:34,668 --> 01:13:37,008
to lead the charge away from sacrificing

1691
01:13:37,008 --> 01:13:38,368
animals to the gods of science.

1692
01:13:38,668 --> 01:13:41,368
So my center has three main pillars.

1693
01:13:41,588 --> 01:13:44,608
We have a biomedical research pillar
where we develop,

1694
01:13:45,328 --> 01:13:47,608
validate, and promote animal free
technologies

1695
01:13:47,668 --> 01:13:48,768
for biomedical research

1696
01:13:48,828 --> 01:13:50,808
to understand human disease processes.

1697
01:13:50,808 --> 01:13:53,648
This is where we use these 3D bioprinted
tissue models

1698
01:13:54,028 --> 01:13:57,688
and we create insulin resistance in our
liver tissue model

1699
01:13:57,748 --> 01:13:58,928
and so much more.

1700
01:13:59,068 --> 01:14:02,328
We have a large number of research
projects looking at

1701
01:14:02,628 --> 01:14:05,448
how we develop disease, understanding
disease mechanisms,

1702
01:14:05,448 --> 01:14:07,368
and then also looking at drug toxicity.

1703
01:14:07,668 --> 01:14:10,688
We have a regulatory pillar where we work

1704
01:14:10,688 --> 01:14:14,888
with regulators like Health Canada to
modernize toxicology

1705
01:14:14,948 --> 01:14:16,568
and chemical safety testing in Canada.

1706
01:14:16,788 --> 01:14:19,968
And one of my favorite pillars is the
academic pillar.

1707
01:14:20,118 --> 01:14:23,728
This is where I'm developing cutting edge
academic programs

1708
01:14:23,788 --> 01:14:26,568
to train the next generation to think
outside the cage.

1709
01:14:27,518 --> 01:14:30,848
What the future of medicine is moving
towards is an era

1710
01:14:31,068 --> 01:14:32,768
of personalized medicine

1711
01:14:33,068 --> 01:14:35,048
and actually this is starting to happen
now.

1712
01:14:35,068 --> 01:14:39,168
People with diseases can have their
diseases

1713
01:14:39,728 --> 01:14:42,768
actually tested against different drugs
and vaccines.

1714
01:14:43,228 --> 01:14:46,168
So if I were to develop a breast cancer,
for example,

1715
01:14:47,188 --> 01:14:51,968
my biology, my tissues can be recreated
in these new

1716
01:14:51,968 --> 01:14:55,968
testing methods to screen for different
drugs

1717
01:14:56,148 --> 01:14:58,888
to see whether those drugs will be
effective against my

1718
01:14:58,888 --> 01:15:01,368
disease and will be safe in my biology.

1719
01:15:02,148 --> 01:15:04,968
That's the era of personalized medicine
we're heading towards.

1720
01:15:05,158 --> 01:15:07,888
Imagine this high throughput system where
you have

1721
01:15:08,608 --> 01:15:10,288
thousands of different patient avatars

1722
01:15:10,418 --> 01:15:11,768
where it's patient derived samples

1723
01:15:12,308 --> 01:15:14,928
and you could test so many drugs at the
same time

1724
01:15:15,108 --> 01:15:16,768
or like pick out the best ones

1725
01:15:16,788 --> 01:15:20,288
and choose that one to test on a patient
instead of waiting

1726
01:15:20,388 --> 01:15:23,768
to grow a disease in an animal model

1727
01:15:23,868 --> 01:15:25,768
and then waiting for them

1728
01:15:25,828 --> 01:15:27,568
to respond to the treatment or not.

1729
01:15:27,628 --> 01:15:29,328
It takes a long time, like, patient's
dying.

1730
01:15:29,328 --> 01:15:31,408
They need to know now like what, what can
be done?

1731
01:15:31,768 --> 01:15:34,168
I hadn't felt this sense of possibility
since the day

1732
01:15:34,168 --> 01:15:37,408
before I accidentally saw my therapist
had written "ugly

1733
01:15:37,618 --> 01:15:38,888
crier" on her notepad.

1734
01:15:39,188 --> 01:15:40,448
And yet, I had to ask,

1735
01:15:40,558 --> 01:15:42,848
because this all started with my
depression,

1736
01:15:43,038 --> 01:15:45,168
what could these new methods do for my
illness?

1737
01:15:45,518 --> 01:15:48,448
Obviously, mental health is one of the
things that is

1738
01:15:49,358 --> 01:15:52,728
huge in terms of our society and needing
to address it.

1739
01:15:52,828 --> 01:15:56,048
So there is a lot of opportunity to
actually not only

1740
01:15:56,938 --> 01:15:59,208
understand how the different

1741
01:15:59,768 --> 01:16:02,928
compounds affect the brain cells in a way

1742
01:16:02,928 --> 01:16:04,368
that either enhances

1743
01:16:04,388 --> 01:16:07,288
or reduces things that are associated
with anxiety

1744
01:16:07,628 --> 01:16:10,488
or depression, but also thinking about

1745
01:16:10,588 --> 01:16:12,808
how do we actually come up with new
solutions,

1746
01:16:12,828 --> 01:16:15,888
new treatments for this that doesn't
require compounds

1747
01:16:16,068 --> 01:16:19,128
or actually can synergize with other
things like being able

1748
01:16:19,128 --> 01:16:23,488
to have more relaxation time or other
things like that.

